      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Commercial CFD solver with documented verification test suite and version-controlled simulation files.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2022 R2 was used under a validated software environment. Version control via Git repository and documented solver release notes confirm compliance with Gradation 2 SQA requirements for MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver passes standard benchmark verification cases relevant to rotating machinery and viscous flow.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent has been verified against Taylor-Couette flow and lid-driven cavity benchmarks. Published verification documentation from the solver vendor satisfies MRL 2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) reported for all quantities of interest; discretization error bounded to within 5% for hemolysis index and shear stress distributions.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted with element counts of 2.1M, 4.6M, and 9.8M cells. GCI values were computed for pressure rise and bulk flow metrics, showing convergence within engineering tolerances. The assessment team notes that near-wall shear stress resolution in the impeller tip clearance region showed mesh sensitivity at the finer levels, but this was considered acceptable given the overall agreement with experimental hemolysis trends. The GCI for the hemolysis-relevant shear stress quantity was not formally bounded per the Gradation 3 requirement, as the team judged the qualitative convergence trend sufficient for the intended comparative use."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions documented and traceable; flow rate and rotational speed match CFD boundary conditions within ±3%.",
      "rationale": "FDA benchmark experimental data specifies flow rates of 2.5–7 L/min and rotational speeds of 2000–3500 RPM. CFD boundary conditions were set to match reported experimental values. Traceability documented in the validation report."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison of CFD-predicted hemolysis index against experimental measurements with error metrics reported.",
      "rationale": "Predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) was compared against FDA benchmark experimental data at 5 operating points. Mean absolute error of 18% was observed, consistent with published CFD hemolysis literature variability and within the acceptance threshold for comparative assessments."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantities of interest in the validation study are directly relevant to the COU hemolysis prediction objectives.",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI — normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) derived from the power-law hemolysis model — directly corresponds to the COU acceptance criterion of relative hemolysis index RH < 1. Validation QoIs are well-aligned with decision-relevant outputs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities performed on geometry and operating conditions sufficiently similar to the COU device and operating envelope.",
      "rationale": "Validation was performed on the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump, which shares the same impeller topology as the COU device. Operating conditions span the clinical CPB envelope of 2.5–7 L/min. Geometric similarity and operating range overlap justify applicability of validation evidence to the COU."
    },
    {
